title: Led Zeppelin - 1971.09.04 Toronto, Canada
description:
Led Zeppelin - 1971.09.04 Toronto, Canada   

Led Zeppelin, Maple Leaf Gardens
September 4, 1971, Toronto, Ontario 

SEPTEMBER 4 - MAPLE LEAF GARDENS, TORONTO, ONTARIO, CANADA (SATURDAY, 8pm)
Ritchie Yorke introduced the band. The show started almost two hours late.

Master > Open Reel

Source: 
Incomplete excellent soundboard recording. 47 minutes.

Details: 
The recording is a very good balanced professional board tape.

Tracklist:
1. Stairway To Heaven
2. Celebration Day
3. That's The Way
4. Going To California
5. What Is And What Should Never Be
6. Moby Dick

Comments: 
A pretty good show, but the band seems to be a bit tired after the last night. 
Worth having for A great version of Celebration Day with Jones' bass going nuts. Plant asking the audience to being quiet during acoustic set: "Listen. It realy amazes me, because anybody who's been to England knows that when you go to a concert, there's such a thing as listening to what's going on! Unfortunately, we're faced with the problem in our free society where a lot of people come to listen, and there's a lot of people who are making a racket so nobody hears what's going on. We've got some things to say but every time I go to open my mouth, there's another spokesman ... If the guy next to you is trying to listen, you've got to respect that and be quiet". So the whole thing's a bit circular respect thing. So many of those big festivals felt apartbecause the respect wasn't a uniform one, and the thing with these concerts is that they normally are!
